quran[8]{c,v,t,f}:
3,187,"And recall when Allah took a covenant from those who were given the Book: 'You shall explain it to men and not hide it. {1} Then they cast the Book behind their backs, and sold it away for a trivial gain. Evil indeed is their bargain.",footnotes:1:Although the Jews remembered that some Prophets had been endowed with the miracle of consuming fire
3,188,"Do not think that those who exult in their misdeeds and love to be praised for what indeed they have not done, {1} do not think that they are secure from chastisement. A painful chastisement awaits them.",footnotes:1:Such people expected praises to be lavished upon them for being God-fearing
3,189,"To Allah belongs the dominion of the heavens and the earth; and Allah is All-Powerful. indeed been successful."
3,190,"Surely in the creation of the heavens and the earth, {1} and in the alternation of night and day, there are signs for men of understanding.",footnotes:1:This section constitutes the conclusion of the present surah. It is related not so much to the verses which immediately precede it as to the entire surah. In order to grasp its significance one should particularly bear in mind our introductory remarks to this surah. (See pp. 229 ff. above.)
3,191,"those who remember Allah while standing, sitting or (reclining) on their backs, and reflect in the creation of the heavens and the earth, {1} (saying): 'Our Lord! You have not created this in vain. Glory to You! Save us, then, from the chastisement of the Fire. {2}",footnotes:1:This means that with the help of those signs one can easily arrive at the Truth
3,192,"Our Lord! Whomever You cause to enter the Fire, him You indeed bring to disgrace, and there will be none to succour the wrong-doers."
3,193,"Our Lord! Indeed we heard a crier calling to the faith saying: "Believe in your Lord"; so we did believe. {1} Our Lord, forgive us our sins, and wipe out our evil deeds and make us die with the truly pious.'",footnotes:1:Many eras have passed before you. Go about
3,194,"'Our Lord, fulfil what You promised to us through Your Messengers, and disgrace us not on the Day of Resurrection; indeed You never go back on Your promise. {1}",footnotes:1:Such people do not doubt the fact that God will fulfil His promises. What they do doubt is whether they will be reckoned among those for whom those promises were made. Hence they pray to God to make them worthy of His promised rewards. They are afraid lest they remain targets of slander and ridicule by the unbelievers in this world
